This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with understanding and characterizing how people interact in information-seeking conversations, which is a natural language processing task. It could also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as it involves analyzing information-seeking conversations. Additionally, the paper discusses the design of conversational search systems, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.HCI (Human-Computer Interaction). The use of crowdsourcing for annotations could also make it relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Finally, the paper mentions the use of patterns in user intent, which could be relevant to cs.LG (Machine Learning).
